- VSCode Version: 1.5.3, but same on insider build f62883f
- OS Version: Windows

Running an extension with the following code:

``` typescript
'use strict';
import * as vscode from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider('haxe', {
        provideCompletionItems(doc, pos) {
            return [new vscode.CompletionItem(':foo'), new vscode.CompletionItem('bar')];
        }
    }, "@");
}
```

Instead of filtering the results, typing a `:` closes the completion list:

![](http://i.imgur.com/9KD0dD9.gif)

Typing letters works as expected though:

![](http://i.imgur.com/VnIOBNK.gif)

This leads to some unexpected behavior in the vshaxe extension: https://github.com/vshaxe/vshaxe/issues/48

Testing https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/12595

See https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/workbench/api/node/extHostTerminalService.ts#L44

``` typescript
public get processId(): Thenable<number> {
    this._checkDisposed();
    if (this._processId) {
        return Promise.resolve<number>(this._processId);
    }
    setTimeout(() => {
        return this.processId;
    }, 200);
}
```

First of all, if you reach the `setTimeout`, there is no return value after all (just `undefined`). And then, how do you know that the process id is there after 200ms?

Testing #12595 

```
context.subscriptions.push(vscode.commands.registerCommand('extension.createTerminal', () => {
        if (!myTerminal) {
            myTerminal = vscode.window.createTerminal('my terminal', 'bash', ['-v']);
            myTerminal.processId.then(value => {
                vscode.window.setStatusBarMessage('' + value);
            });
        }
    }));
```

Above code fails because, myTerminal.process is null. 
This is not expected because it is a promise.

- VSCode Version: 1.5.3
- OS Version: Windows 10 64-bit

Hi there, I'm the developer behind [HTML CSS Class Completion](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=Zignd.html-css-class-completion) and it seems to be causing trouble for lot of people and the reason for that is an issue that I'm failing to find a solution, I come here to ask for help or assistence to resolve this issue. I have been reported several time in many issues here on VS Code repository, but @AurelioDeRosa managed to reproduce the issue and documented the steps [here](https://github.com/Zignd/HTML-CSS-Class-Completion/issues/12#issuecomment-246828941).

I've managed to identify what could might be causing the issue, it basically happens here:

[**src/extension.ts#L36-L63**](https://github.com/Zignd/HTML-CSS-Class-Completion/blob/master/src/extension.ts#L36-L63)

```
return async.each(uris, async (uri, callback) => {
    try {
        Array.prototype.push.apply(definitions, await ParseEngineGateway.callParser(uri));
        callback();
    } catch (error) {
        failedLogs += `${uri.path}\n`;
        failedLogsCount++;
        callback();
    }
}, (error) => {
    if (error) {
        console.error('Failed to parse the documents: ', error);
        return reject(error);
    }

    uniqueDefinitions = _.uniqBy(definitions, (x) => x.className);

    // ...removed to shorten the post

    notifier.notify('zap', 'CSS classes cached (click to cache again)');

    return resolve();
});
```

At this point the extension parse the found CSS files in asynchronously and in parallel. During debugging I managed to identify that at the beginning some files manage to get parsed, but then VS Code and the extension freezes. I'd like to understand what I'm doing wrong, so that I can fix the issue, but I have run out of ideas on how to resolve it.

Thanks in advance.
